  footnotes: []
english:
  title: At the Sorae Temple on Byeonsan Mountain
  author: Jung Jisung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The ancient path lies silent, wound through pine roots,
    the sky drawn so near I could touch the Pleiades.
    Floating clouds and flowing waters—a traveler arrives at the temple,
    where among crimson leaves and verdant moss, the monk has shut his door.

    Autumn wind, soft and cool, blows across the setting sun,
    while the mountain moon grows luminous and distant gibbons cry.
    Strange and wondrous—that old monk with his long brows,
    who through long years has never dreamed of human clamor.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Pleiades (Dou and Niu in Classical Chinese astronomy) represent stars near the zenith, emphasizing the temple's remote mountain height.
  - key: ''
    value: The imagery of sealed doors and untouched dreams reflects the Buddhist ideal of withdrawal from worldly attachments.
